<div class="heading-black-smaller">Create oxygen O<sub>2</sub> and absorb carbon dioxide CO<sub>2</sub></div>
Plants and trees create more oxygen than they consume for growth. Green plants absorb also harmful gasses as Sulphur dioxide SO<sub>2</sub>, Nitrogen dioxide NO<sub>2</sub>, Carbon monoxide CO.<br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Decrease air temperature</div>
One hectare of forest evaporates up to 350 liters (92 gallons) of water per hour and decrease air temperature about 6 - 9˚C. (43 - 48˚F)<br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Soil Repair</div>
Tree roots fix soil in slopes and banks and protect it against erosion. <br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Decrease noise</div>
A strip of trees 10 meters (32 feet) wide decrease noise up to 6 dB. Leafed trees absorb 26% sound (acoustic energy) and 74% return and disperse (often use as noise barrier). <br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Dust and micro-organism absorption</div>
Leafs act as filters for dust. Trees are able to catch 27% of dust in towns. Trees creates substances to kill pathogenic germs as antibiotics. There is up to 200-times less bacteria in coniferous forest than in street in town.<br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Hold moisture and clean water</div>
Forests work as sponges during rain and help reduce flooding.<br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Increase biodiversity</div>
Trees create shelters and homes for several kinds of plants and animals. <br/>
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Industrial value</div>
Fruit, Wood for decoration, paper production, fire, .... Leafs, bark and flowers for medicines. <br/> 
<br/><div class="heading-black-smaller">Social value</div>
Forests, parks are used for relaxation and meetings of families, friends, people.
